      <prompt>
        <p>Biological buffer systems use weak acids to prevent large changes in pH.</p>
        <p>Which of the following is not a major contributor to the pH buffer system?</p>
      </prompt>
      <simpleChoice identifier="CHOICE_000">Bicarbonate</simpleChoice>
      <simpleChoice identifier="CHOICE_001">Carbon dioxide</simpleChoice>
      <simpleChoice identifier="CHOICE_002">Proteins</simpleChoice>
      <simpleChoice identifier="CHOICE_003">Phosphate</simpleChoice>
      <simpleChoice identifier="CHOICE_004">White blood cells</simpleChoice>
    </choiceInteraction>
  </itemBody>
  <modalFeedback identifier="CORRECT_FEEDBACK" outcomeIdentifier="GENERAL_FEEDBACK" showHide="show">
    <p>
      <b>Option E (White blood cells) is Correct.</b>
      There are three major buffer systems that are involved in maintaining a relatively constant pH in body fluids. They are:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>Bicarbonate/carbon dioxide</li>
      <li>Proteins, particularly haemoglobin</li>
      <li>Phosphate.</li>
    </ol>
    <br/>
    <p>
      <b>Option A (Bicarbonate) is Incorrect.</b>
      Bicarbonate is a biological buffer.
